SIMPLE: insecta
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insecta
<hw>In*sec"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See
<er>Insect</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the
classes of <phylum>Arthropoda</phylum>, including those that have one
pair of antenn⟦ae⟧, three pairs of mouth organs, and breathe air by
means of trache⟦ae⟧, opening by spiracles along the sides of the body.
In this sense it includes the Hexapoda, or six-legged insects and the
Myriapoda, with numerous legs. See <er>Insect</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>In a more restricted sense, the
Hexapoda alone. See <er>Hexapoda</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>In the most general sense, the
Hexapoda, Myriapoda, and Arachnoidea, combined.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The typical Insecta, or hexapod insects, are divided
into several orders, viz.: <styp><ord>Hymenoptera</ord></styp>, as the
bees and ants; <styp><ord>Diptera</ord></styp>, as the common flies,
gnats, and mosquitos; <styp><ord>Aphaniptera</ord></styp>, or fleas;
<styp><ord>Lepidoptera</ord></styp>, or moths and butterflies;
<styp><ord>Neuroptera</ord></styp>, as the ant-lions and hellgamite;
<styp><ord>Coleoptera</ord></styp>, or beetles;
<styp><ord>Hemiptera</ord></styp>, as bugs, lice, aphids;
<styp><ord>Orthoptera</ord></styp>, as grasshoppers and cockroaches;
<styp><ord>Pseudoneuroptera</ord></styp>, as the dragon flies and
termites; <styp><ord>Euplexoptera</ord></styp>, or earwigs;
<styp><ord>Thysanura</ord></styp>, as the springtails, podura, and
lepisma. See these words in the Vocabulary.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insectary</ent>⟦br⟧
